\section{Detect Aura}
\label{detect-aura}
\index{detect aura}

{\bf Note} These rules cover the detect aura talents of the Namer,
Earth and Celestial Colleges.  The Detect Aura Talent is defined, then
guide lines to its use are defined.  Finally further notes and
examples are appended for full clarification.  The general rules and
observations will apply to most detect aura magic unless specifically
stated to the contrary in the description of that magic.
d68 2
d72 1
d75 3
a77 3
\basechance{Perception (\x2 for Namers) \\
\hspace{1em}+ 5\% / Rank \\
\hspace{1em}- 1\% for every foot after the first five feet the target is from Adept}
d81 13
a93 7
All living beings have an aura.  Formerly living things retain their
name and traces of their aura.  Magic also has its own aura, but this
is weaker again.  This aura may be read by the use of magic for clues
concerning the nature of an entity or object.  Objects made of
formerly living matter will also possess an aura, but one which is
much weaker.  The following categories of auras are listed in order of
strength (weakest to strongest):
d95 10
a104 26
\begin{Enumerate}
\item Magical
\item Formerly living as part of an object
\item Formerly living (not including undead)
\item Living plants
\item Non-sentient undead and golems
\item Living animals
\item Sentient plants
\item Sentient undead and golems
\item Short-living sentient beings -- humans, dwarves, giants, etc
\item Long-living sentient beings -- dragons, elves, titans, demons, etc
\end{Enumerate}

Whenever an Adept can directly see an entity, object or area, they may
tell the GM that they are attempting to detect the being or object's
aura.  D100 is rolled.  If the result is less than or equal to the
Adept's Base Chance, the GM must tell the Adept which of the
aforementioned categories of aura they are seeing (with the strongest
taking precedence), and answer one question of the Adept's choice
about the being or object (Namers may get additional information, as
listed under that college). The question must be intrinsic to that
entity or object.  It is not possible to determine Individual True
Name of the entity.  If the dice roll falls within the span of
possible results necessary to achieve double or triple effects when
casting a spell, the Adept may ask the GM two (for double effect) or
three (for triple effect) questions.
a107 31
\subsection{General Rules and Observations}

\begin{Enumerate}
\item
The answer to a DA question will consist of a single concept or
``bit'' of information.
\item
Any one part of an object will be representative of the entire object.
\item
Only one attempt at Detect Aura may be made per object.  An individual
object will change over time, however, and a fresh attempt may be made
when the aura has changed sufficiently to class it as a ``new'' object.
\item
If an aura has been successfully read, the answer(s) to the
question(s) asked will be available without a new Cast Check being
made, until such time that the object changes sufficiently to be
considered a ``new'' object.

\item
To see an aura requires direct line of sight to the object being DAed.
It is not possible to DA through a mirror, crystal ball, or Wizard's
Eye, or by any other indirect means.

\item
Illusions do not usually provide an accompanying aura.  Thus most
illusions will have the aura of magical.

\item
In combat, a Detect Aura and question requires a pass action.
\end{Enumerate}

