In general the more specific the question the more specific the answer
-- the exact nature is left to the GM's discretion.

\begin{example}
``What was the last type of magic to impact on this person?''  might get
``A spell'' \\
``What is the nature of the most recent magical affect on
this person?'' might get ``fortitude'' \\
``What was the last spell to impact on this person?'' might get
``Strength of Stone'' \\
\end{example}

Note that the information must be intrinsic to that object -- a
formerly living body will not have a magical college or a skill --
those are properties of living beings only.

\item
A DA of a big toe sticking out from underneath a blanket will reveal
the same information as if the entire being were visible.  A detached
thumb could reveal some information about its former owner, up to the
time it was detached, providing it is intrinsic to the thumb, for
example generic true name, plane of origin, or age.

\item

All things change over time, even if outwardly they look the same.
While the times may vary from object to object depending on
circumstances, they tend to relate to a three month cycle following
the seasons. An object DAed in Spring will have changed sufficiently
by Summer to be able to be DAed again. Thus if the attempt at a DA
fails, any attempt to read the aura again before the object has
changed enough to be considered a ``new'' object (that is next season)
the DA will fail again.  Similarly, if the attempt succeeds, the aura
may not be detected again to ask another question, until next season.
The single attempt rule also applies to multi-hex objects.  Only one
DA may be performed per item -- one cannot DA a wooden floor three
times just because it covers 3 hexes.  Attempts to do so will get the
response (even before rolling the dice) -- ``you see an aura, formerly
